## 10. Phase 8 — Package & Deploy an Application

You will package 7-Zip as a Win32 app and deploy it to the device via Intune. This demonstrates the full app packaging and deployment workflow used in real organisations.

### 10.1 Package 7-Zip with IntuneWinAppUtil.exe

**Run this in PowerShell or Command Prompt on your host machine (not the VM):**

```powershell
# Navigate to where you saved the tool
cd C:\Tools

# Run the packaging tool
.\IntuneWinAppUtil.exe -c "C:\Tools\7zip" -s "7z2301-x64.exe" -o "C:\Tools\output"
```

**Parameters explained:**
- `-c` = **source folder** containing the installer (`C:\Tools\7zip`)
- `-s` = **setup file** — the specific installer filename (`7z2301-x64.exe`)
- `-o` = **output folder** where the `.intunewin` file will be saved (`C:\Tools\output`)

When prompted: **"Do you want to encrypt the content and enable the option for advanced encryption?"** → Type `N` and press Enter.

The tool will create: `C:\Tools\output\7z2301-x64.intunewin`

📸 **SCREENSHOT:** `08-packaging-output.png` — The command prompt/PowerShell window showing the IntuneWinAppUtil.exe output, including the line confirming the `.intunewin` file was created.

### 10.2 Find the 7-Zip Silent Install Command

For any app you package, you need to know the **silent install command** (runs without showing a UI to the user) and the **uninstall command**.

For 7-Zip:
- **Install command:** `7z2301-x64.exe /S`  
  (`/S` = silent install — no UI shown)
- **Uninstall command:** `MsiExec.exe /X{23170F69-40C1-2702-2301-000001000000} /qn`  
  (The GUID changes per version — verify yours by installing 7-Zip on a test machine and checking Programs & Features → right-click → look at the uninstall string in the registry at `HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Uninstall`)

> **Tip:** To find the uninstall string via PowerShell:
> ```powershell
> Get-ItemProperty "HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Uninstall\*" |
>   Where-Object { $_.DisplayName -like "*7-zip*" } |
>   Select-Object DisplayName, UninstallString
> ```

### 10.3 Add the App in Intune

1. In Intune: **Apps → Windows → Add**
2. App type: **Windows app (Win32)**
3. Click **Select**

**Tab 1 — App information:**
- Click **Select app package file** → browse to `C:\Tools\output\7z2301-x64.intunewin`
- After upload, fill in:
  - Name: `7-Zip 23.01`
  - Description: `Open source file archiver and compression tool`
  - Publisher: `Igor Pavlov`
  - App version: `23.01`
  - Category: **Utilities**
  - Display this as a featured app in the Company Portal: **No**
  - Information URL: `https://www.7-zip.org`
  - Privacy URL: (leave blank)
  - Developer: `Igor Pavlov`
  - Owner: `IT Department`
  - Notes: `Deployed via Intune as part of Autopilot standard build`
  - Logo: optionally download the 7-Zip logo and upload it

**Tab 2 — Program:**
| Setting | Value |
|---|---|
| Install command | `7z2301-x64.exe /S` |
| Uninstall command | `MsiExec.exe /X{23170F69-40C1-2702-2301-000001000000} /qn` |
| Install behaviour | **System** (installs for all users, not just current user) |
| Device restart behaviour | **App install may force a device restart** |
| Return codes | Leave defaults (0 = success, 1707 = success, 3010 = soft reboot, 1641 = hard reboot, 1618 = retry) |

**Tab 3 — Requirements:**
| Setting | Value |
|---|---|
| Operating system architecture | **64-bit** |
| Minimum operating system | **Windows 10 21H1** |

**Tab 4 — Detection rules:**

Detection rules tell Intune whether 7-Zip is already installed on a device (so it doesn't reinstall unnecessarily).

Rule format: **Manually configure detection rules → Add**

| Setting | Value |
