## 14. Interview Talking Points

This section maps your lab experience to common interview questions for 1st/2nd line IT support roles in the UK.

---

**"Tell me about your experience with Intune / endpoint management."**

> "I've built a hands-on lab where I set up a complete Microsoft Intune environment from scratch, including Windows Autopilot for zero-touch device deployment. I registered devices using the hardware hash extraction tool, created deployment profiles, configured the Enrollment Status Page, applied security baselines, and deployed applications using the Win32 content prep tool. I also created compliance policies covering BitLocker, Defender, and password requirements, and mapped the non-compliance actions. I've documented the whole process, including the issues I hit and how I resolved them."

---

**"What is Windows Autopilot and how does it work?"**

> "Autopilot is Microsoft's zero-touch deployment solution. When a device is powered on for the first time, it connects to the internet and checks its hardware hash against the Autopilot service. If the device is registered, instead of going through the standard Windows setup, it goes through a company-specific experience — applying branding, installing required apps, and joining Azure AD — without any IT technician needing to touch the device physically. The Enrollment Status Page blocks the user from using the device until everything is configured. It's commonly used for remote workers or when sending devices directly from the manufacturer to the end user."

---

**"What is the Enrollment Status Page and why is it important?"**

> "The ESP is a progress screen shown during Autopilot provisioning. It blocks the user from accessing the desktop until all required apps and configuration profiles have been applied. This is important because if a user got to the desktop before, say, security policies were applied, they could have a window where their device doesn't meet company security standards. The ESP closes that window. It also shows a clear progress indicator so the user knows what's happening, and it can be configured to show a custom IT support message if something goes wrong."

---

**"How do you deploy software via Intune?"**

> "For Win32 apps — standard .exe or .msi installers — you use the IntuneWinAppUtil tool to package the installer into a .intunewin format. You then create a Win32 app in Intune, specifying the install and uninstall command-line strings, the requirements (OS version, architecture), and a detection rule so Intune knows whether the app is already installed. The detection rule is important — if it's wrong, Intune will either reinstall the app every time or never detect it as installed. I used a file-based detection rule checking for the app's main executable. Apps are then assigned as Required (force-installed) or Available (user can install from Company Portal)."

---

**"What does a compliance policy do in Intune?"**

> "A compliance policy defines the security baseline a device must meet. In my lab I configured it to require BitLocker encryption, Defender running with up-to-date definitions, a minimum OS build version, secure boot enabled, and a password policy. If a device fails any of those checks, Intune marks it as non-compliant. You can then configure what happens — in my setup, the device is immediately marked non-compliant, the user gets an email after one day, and after 30 days the device is retired. When compliance is combined with Conditional Access (Project 03), a non-compliant device also gets blocked from accessing Microsoft 365 services."

---

**"How would you troubleshoot a device that's not enrolling via Autopilot?"**

> "I'd work through it systematically. First, check that the device's hardware hash is actually registered in Intune's Autopilot devices list and that the profile status shows Assigned — not Not assigned. Then check group membership: the device needs to be in the group the deployment profile is assigned to. If registration and assignment look right, I'd check network connectivity at OOBE using Shift+F10 to get a command prompt and pinging a known address. I'd also check the vTPM or physical TPM is enabled, since Autopilot and Windows 11 both require TPM 2.0. If the device gets through Autopilot but the ESP fails, I'd collect the MDM diagnostic logs using Ctrl+Shift+Alt+F3 and look for the specific app or policy that's failing."

---

**"What's the difference between a configuration profile and a compliance policy?"**

> "A configuration profile actively pushes settings to the device — it tells Windows what to do: set the wallpaper to this, block the Microsoft Store, defer Windows Updates by 7 days. The device applies those settings regardless of its state. A compliance policy, on the other hand, checks whether the device meets certain requirements — does it have BitLocker on, is Defender running, is the OS up to date. It's read-only from a configuration perspective; it doesn't change settings, it just evaluates them. The two work together: configuration profiles set the state you want, and compliance policies verify that state is maintained."

